    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-05-14T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-05-14T01:00:00-05:00" n="19"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d19">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01 Manchuria/207: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1"
                            type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary
                            of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-05-14T14:00:00+08:00"
                            >May 14, 1932—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 14—3:14 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>531. Following from American Consul General at Harbin: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“May 13, noon.</p>
                        <list>
                            <label>1.</label>
                            <item>Japanese troops from the south still continue to arrive at Harbin.
                                Difficult to ascertain numbers. They are being sent east along the
                                Chinese Eastern Railway and down the Sungari River towards Sansing
                                engaging old Kirin forces and brigands en route.</item>
                            <label>2.</label>
                            <item>There is danger that the west line of the railway might soon be
                                cut near Anda Station in the vicinity of which are concentrated
                                breastworks and troops of General <persName
                                    corresp="frus1932v03#p_MC1">Ma Chan-shan</persName>, who appears
                                definitely <pb facs="0114" n="16" xml:id="pg_16"/> to be opposing
                                with force Japanese military advances in Heilungkiang.”</item>
                        </list>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
